text.text:
a delightful shopping destination for anyone looking for quality food and household essentials. Upon entering, the store has a clean and organized layout, making it easy to navigate through the aisles. The bright lighting and vibrant displays of fresh produce immediately catch the eye, showcasing a wide variety of fruits and vegetables that are both seasonal and locally sourced.

The selection of products is impressive, ranging from organic items to everyday staples. The bakery section deserves a special mention, as the aroma of freshly baked bread and pastries fills the air, enticing customers to indulge in a sweet treat or two. The deli counter offers a fantastic selection of meats and cheeses, with staff members always ready to provide recommendations or sample tastings.

One of the standout features of FreshMart is its commitment to sustainability. The store offers several eco-friendly products and encourages customers to bring their own bags. Additionally, there’s a section dedicated to plant-based and gluten-free options, catering to diverse dietary preferences.

Customer service is generally friendly and helpful, though during peak hours, the checkout lines can get a bit long. It might be beneficial for the store to consider adding more registers during busy times to enhance the shopping experience.

text.text:
PLEASE READ!
Experienced Former Retail Store Manger here. Today while I was at the self checkout at Star Market, 1065 Commonwealth Ave (Store #3588), I overheard a troubling loud situation at the service desk and decided Id stick around a bit to see how it would be handled. A customer was aggressively yelling at a worker—completely inappropriate behavior. The employee Dayana remained calm, professional, and tried her best to help despite being treated with hostility and disrespect.

She eventually called for help, which was absolutely the right thing to do. But instead of supporting her, Ludgero, who Ive just found out is STORE DIRECTOR ( according to store receipts!) showed up and made the situation worse. I clearly heard him say to her “Next time I will fire you for that.” as I was walking by ready to head out.

Not a word to the angry customer. No support for his staff. Just a cold threat to an employee who was visibly shaken up and still trying to do her job.

That is unacceptable. This employee handled herself with composure under pressure, and she deserved to be backed up not intimidated by her own manager. If this is how Star Market management treats their staff in front of customers, it reflects a toxic and broken leadership culture.

I sincerely hope corporate sees this because that manager owes her an apology, and Star Market owes her better.

If you shop here and care about how employees are treated, speak up. No one should fear losing their job for handling an abusive customer the right way!!

I drive for a living, primarily in the Boston area. There are a number of grocery stores that I count on for use of the restroom, because they all have public restrooms and most of them have adequate parking. This star market is one of the locations that I frequently use. Whenever I do use one of these restrooms, I always buy myself a beverage and a snack, even if I don't need one. Recently most of the Boston star market locations have started locking their restroom
doors, which is fine because I just ask someone there to let me in and they always do (Even though every location's bathroom is filthy and covered in urine). This location is no different, however, I've learned what absolute jerks all of the employees are. While every one of them does open the door for me, they make me feel like I'm ruining their day for it. That's okay though. The new stop & shop up the street is really nice. I'll just give them my $5 every time I need to use the bathroom.

text.text:
I am very sad to change this review from 5-stars to 3 stars.

Plenty about this place still slaps -- the spice wall is unrivaled, great ramen selection, frozen paneer and breads, as well as dosa batter.

The prices have evidently gone up. I went recently and paid almost $60 for a single bag of groceries -- granted, here's what I got:

- 2x Haldiram large blocks of paneer (800g)
- 1x Deep's small bag of kashmiri chili powder (200g)
- 1x Deep's small bag of garam masala (200g)
- 1x Haldiram family size bag of aloo paratha (1.6kg)

Looking online, I am able to assemble many carts that beat this price. I would rather shop in person, but $60 for this cart is very unreasonable, especially considering there are many Indian students living nearby with few other options.

I understand the high prices may not be the fault of this store, but the prices have gotten out of hand.

Still, I love this store.

text.text:
Wild Duck Market

The market in Bakbay is a true gem, offering a wide range of everyday essentials, groceries, and more. I was delighted to find several gluten-free options, as well as international ones. While the selection of fruits and vegetables is modest, it covers the basics well, and everything looks fresh.

What really stands out is how competitively priced the items are—nothing feels overpriced, which is such a relief compared to other places. Having this market right in the neighborhood is incredibly convenient, saving me the hassle of driving to larger supermarkets.

The staff are also the nicest people, always ready to help with a smile, which adds to the welcoming atmosphere. I really appreciate having such a well-rounded, affordable local market close to home. It’s a valuable addition to the community!

text.text:
This is a tough review to write. I want to like this little deli so much. I work nearby and it's one of the most convenient options for a quick bite to eat. Ive visited probably a dozen times at this point, and every time I've hoped for improvement but it's just not happening so here goes.

The good: fresh ingredients and bread and relatively quick service, All things considered.

The bad: The menu is a disaster. They have paper menus which include in the ballpark of 30 different sandwiches and paninis. They also have little placards floating around with additional handwritten options, as well as a specials board that adds even more different items everyday. In total, I'd wager that they offer around 40 different sandwich options. One would think that means that there's something for everyone, unfortunately that's not the case though. They don't have any of the traditional staples-- no Italian, no chicken pesto, no chicken Cesar or turkey and Swiss. They do have menu items that start with these sandwiches, but then they add on all sorts of other seemingly random ingredients to create a new sandwich that looks nothing like the original. This wouldn't be a huge problem if it was easy to customize an existing menu item. I've tried doing that again and again though, and literally half the time it's incorrect.

I hope they're able to turn things around. The staff has always been friendly and helpful and I'm certainly rooting for them. I probably won't be back for a while though

text.text:
This Trader Joe's is a must-visit for me every time I’m in Boston visiting my daughter and her family. It’s one of the busiest TJ’s in New England, and it’s easy to see why—great selection, friendly staff, and its prime location in Brookline.

The best-kept secret of this location is the parking situation. While the store's own lot is tiny and chaotic (honestly, an accident waiting to happen), you’re allowed to park at the neighboring business lot. This is a lifesaver, especially during peak hours!

Inside, the store is always bustling. They do a great job keeping shelves stocked despite the constant crowd, and the staff are friendly and helpful, even with the high volume of customers.

One quirk that stands out here is the checkout process. You queue up in a single line, and once you reach the front, you have to watch for the next available cashier to wave you over. It can feel a bit hectic and, at times, inefficient, especially when the line grows long. While it’s not the best system, it seems to work for the space limitations they have.

Overall, this Trader Joe's delivers on the essentials, and despite its quirks, I always leave with everything I came for—and more. Just pack some patience for parking and checkout! Saluti

text.text:
I recently visited this supermarket and was pleasantly surprised by my experience. Compared to larger chains like Stop & Shop and Target, this store offers reasonable prices on a wide variety of products. The selection of milk, vegetables, eggs, and yogurt is impressive, and I appreciate the consistent quality.

What truly stands out is the staff—they are incredibly helpful and respectful, always ready to assist with a smile. I felt welcomed and valued as a customer. The store is well-organized, making it easy to find what I needed.

Overall, this supermarket is a fantastic alternative to the bigger brands. I’ll definitely be returning for my grocery needs!

text.text: My first time here and the store itself is clean, well-lit, and pleasant. Pretty good amount of produce, dairy and meat, and various everyday products. Price is on the "okay" side (not cheap). But there are some good weekly deals one may take advantage of. Most disappointed though, that the online sign up does not work. The verification email does not get sent. Tried multiple times with multiple emails and asked other people to try making an account, no one was able to get the verification email to work. Customer service desk manually put in the details (which I later hated because they got extra information out of me with my Driver's License that was not required to create Account online). But you still have to LINK your card to the online account I cannot create. Got no apologies for this inconvenience and wasting an hour of my time. Customer service (on the phone) was closed for the weekend. The service desk in the Shop told me to call tomorrow as they can't fix the issue, but I don't want to waste more of my own time to fix a company's problem. Found it very frustrating how no-one took ownership and kept saying it must be my email/phone/network that is the issue. And yes, I checked the Spam folder multiple times. Will probably not Shop here unless I super-urgently need something because of the location. Not cheap, bad customer service, even basic online function does not work. Quality of produce and products were okay, cleanliness great, felt safe inside and around the store. Uploading some updated photos as the ones I checked before coming into the store were from 7 years ago. Cheers.

text.text:
Whichever MBA decided to change the bags to brown single ply paper mache with handles attached via a single pass from a kindergartners glue stick should be drawn and quartered.

I tried to gently open one of the bags and it tore all the way down the side. And then when I picked it up by the handle with nothing in it the handle came off in my hand.

You might say, “just bring your own bag!”Which is what I did but I bought a digiornos supreme pizza (bless) and it didn’t fit so that and a box of spinach for my whole quarter of a mile walk home kept trying to leap out of this bag that was torn in half. Resulting in an old lady trying to help me with my groceries.

Look the food is fine, but until you fix your bag situation I’ll be going to Trader Joe’s.

text.text: Who would have predicted that Trader Joe's would become the most affordable grocery chain!?! They really are super affordable! I think their brand is generally very high quality, unique, and there's always something new to try every time I go. I love their unique set-up- I might look for tortellini, and on the same shelf will be a bunch of apple pies, Saigon  cinnamon,.....and just below that, maple and vanilla ice cream...and next I'll see tortilla chips, bagels, sparkling cranberry juice, and pumpkin cookies. So random! But never boring! I always leave excited to dig into whatever new thing Ol' Joe found in his travels 😉

I have fond memories of this place from when I was a child. I like the store and the chain of Trader Joes and this place really sticks out to me. In other stores I usually have a hard time navigating through the people of color, especially the darker ones. I think this store is kept nice and clean, the hispanic workers with curly hair do the job well.  My last trip I spoke to yojana (the kindest girl ever) about the organic prpduce and she was super helpful, then also this other worker andy. These are examples of workers we need now and I believe both of them might be together so he kind of gave me a bit of unwanted attitude. It should be brought up to the super's attention that somehting fishy may be brewing. I urge the managers to take action because he sure is cruisin for a bruisin.

Great store for the organice product, and good prices too!!

Gave them benefit of doubt and thought maybe Apple Maps was out of date or something? So I tried google and the phone # was the same. Hit call from Google, and it rang for a while before it automatically transferred me to customer service… who also didn’t pick up… I’ve seen a couple of rats scurry through the kitchen before, but have always shopped here anyways because it’s local and I like to support the college kids etc who work here. Figured the lobsters are in a tank, so there’s less chance of contamination. I’ve literally never left a google review before I think, but since customer service didn’t care to pick up I guess I’m one of those people now? Kinda feel like shit for leaving this because I had worked retail all during college & now work in store management, but kinda pissed me off that I was lied to & hung up on the first time?? and ignored the second. Just wanted to make my anniversary special 😅

text.text:
Great store. The variety is much better than I thought would be available. The produce, the pre-prepped section with veggies, meats, seafood, sauces. Items like marinated eggs, marinated tofu. A great grab and go noodle bowl for $8 which could easily serve 2-3. Sushi section, Kimchi section, prepped seafood section, frozen and fresh meats.

An enormous variety of soy sauce, hoisin, fish sauce, noodles, meats and seafood. And- so many other things you may not imagine like standard grocery items like nutella, crackers, chips, milk, eggs, spices (eg basil, dill, onion powder), personal hygiene products, pans, utensils, various kitchen gadgets. This is a great sized grocery store ( smaller than regular). Easy to navigate, well laid out, well lit. You can truly do a full grocery shopping here, not just for specialty items.

Customer service was a bit nonexistent. Not unpleasant but no one engaging with me or assisting with my experience. I did observe at least one gentleman who appeared to be security as he lingered in the aisles and repeatedly paused to watch people. He didn't have any belongings or groceries. He nor any other uniformed employee didn't ask if we needed any help. Cashier didn't engage at all other than to ask if we needed a bag.

He nor any other uniformed employee didn't ask if we needed any help. Cashier didn't engage at all other than to ask if we needed a bag.

text.text:
Nice to see an hmart around here.

Parking wasn’t too bad weekday 6pm metered parking.

It’s a smaller hmart than Burlington or Quincy.

They have good quality produce and meats. I got ingredients for hotpot shabu at home. Get also buy pots and butane burner with cans all on sale. The burner was 21, pot 20. On sale! Cheaper than super 88 surprisingly.

Kimbap with veggies pickled radish and jalapeño for $10. Very filling.

I’ll be back to get more groceries for my next dinner party.

Definitely a fun place to explore for something different!

text.text: I went for an ice cream yesterday and didn't pay as much attention at first. Once I reached home, turned out it was completely melted. I went back and told the cashier about this and he said he can't give any refunds. Instead I can go and select any other ice cream I want. When I opened the fridge every other ice cream was melted and there was literally no warning that their fridge had issues. When I requested the cashier to bring their manager as I was only interested in a refund, suddenly he was able to give me a refund. So what I witnessed was someone who blatantly lied to my face to save $7. Really bad experience, I'd rather suggest the grocery store next to it called "College Convinience" it's open 24/7 and if things go bad, then they actually care.

text.text:
I’ll never go back in here if my life depended on it.
After my amazing dentist visit I decided to go grab lunch. From the time I stepped in the building it was all eyes on me. At first I felt like Rihanna, like they just saw a celebrity of some sort but then I noticed I was just being followed. I proceeded to check out at that point because it’s like “really!?”. So I sat down to eat my salad. Let’s not forget to mention how dirty the table was, and the fact that I had to clean it.

I decided that I wanted a drink, I go back to grab a drink and pay for it..after asking for assistance with the payment she proceeds to follow me out asking if I paid for my items. Meanwhile I clearly left the receipt for her to see.

Idk discrimination at its finest. Never again!

text.text:
Large, not overpriced grocery store similar to Safeway or Kroger/Albertsons. Fresh produce, meat, deli, bakery and other departments.

Deli has both hot and cold food. Sandwiches made to order, Chinese food, fried and roasted chicken, sushi, salads, salad bar and much more.

Bakery has bread, desserts, and pastries.

Large dairy department with yogurt, cheese, butter, milk and eggs. There's a separate deli meat and sliced cheese department and a gourmet cheese and set of tapas department.

The meat department seemed small, but it makes sense for the area, which is the tourist center.

Other departments include canned and boxed food, international food, cleaning supplies, paper products, pet products and such like any large grocery store in the US.

Very clean store. Self checkout as well as staffed checkstands. Bags are 5¢ each.

text.text: This grocery store is in a convenient location. It's across the street from the Marriott we were staying at and also in the epicenter of Boston's Back Bay. We got in late Friday night and was able to get some shopping done before the 11pm closing time. The store looked organized with all of your grocery needs. There is a liquor store on the second floor too. Security was on duty so we felt safe. The prices seem comparable to other supermarkets. They also have a rewards program which I didn't look into because I don't have one of these near where I live. There were self checkouts and you can purchase bags for 5 cents a piece. Overall, a nice grocery store located in the city.

text.text: I went to the customer service desk today, waited for a long time even there was only one guy in front of me buying lotteries. Once was my turn, the old lady told the guy behind me to come to the front and helped him first. Because he was there first. Even though he left the line while we were all waiting, after she help that guy with two packs of cigarettes and the lottery machine was fixed, she was attempted to come back to the other person again. I wonder how many time this store's staff was going to play favoritism and breaking the common rules, i wonder if she will tell me to cut other people's line if I was in the line once? BTW the soda stream refills are barely $16/bottle, and it's $31.99/bottle here. Plus the recent two years the produces aren't fresh and often out of stocks and no one refill the shelves, what a robbery and chaotic place.
